Data Handling and Visualisation Final Report: A History of Formula 1¶

The data set used for this report comes from: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rohanrao/formula-1-world-championship-1950-2020?select=results.csv
The data set contains information on the last 70 Formula 1 World Championship seasons. This report uses data from the most recent 50 years, as there was a lot of missing data from the 1952 to 1972 period.
The original data was stored in multiple CSV files, requiring me to create single custom dataframe using the Pandas library and the merge functionality, joining each dataframe based on the common keys found in the corresponding table.
Below is a table showing each attribute in the dataset, as well as a description and a data type.
Attribute Description Type
race_date The date of the race datetime
start_pos Starting position in the race int
final_pos Finishing position in the race int
final_status The final status of the drivers race string
points Points gained from the race float
laps Total laps driven in the race int
fastest_lap The lap number of the drivers fastest lap float
fastest_lap_rank The rank of the drivers fastest lap float
fastest_lap_time The time of the drivers fastest lap string
fastest_lap_speed The fastest lap speed in km/h float
race_name The name of the race string
constructor_name The name of the constructor string
constructor_nationality The nationality of the constructor string
driver_name The name of the driver string
driver_nationality The nationality of the driver string
dob The driver's date of birth datetime

The libraries used in this analysis are Pandas, for reading and storing the data, and manipulating the dataframe; Matplotlib, for creating figures and axes, and customising plot characteristics; and Seaborn, for plotting the data and creating high-level visualisations. The magic command 'matplotlib inline' is used to embed the images generated by the plot 'in' the notebook, rather than in a separate pop-up.

When reading in the data using pandas, the 'race_date' and 'dob' columns are parsed as dates, and the 'race_date' column is then set as the index, allowing us to slice and filter the dataframe by race date, rather than arbitrary numerical indexes.

The Age of Winning Drivers¶

To calculate the age of each winning driver, I've created a new column called 'winner_age', by subtracting the year the driver was born from the year the race took place. I sliced each column using the loc function which takes an index label (the column name) as the parameter. Then, as the datatype of each Series was a datetime object, I was able to directly access the year attribute using the 'dt' method. I also calculated the mean of the winning age distribution using the mean() function, to use for further analysis in addition to the histogram.

In [56]:
# reset the index to make location based slicing easier
winners = winners.reset_index()

# create a new column using the year attributes from the datetime objects
winners.loc[:,'winner_age'] = winners.loc[:,'race_date'].dt.year - winners.loc[:,'dob'].dt.year
In [57]:
# calculate the mean winner's age
print('The mean winning age is:', round(winners['winner_age'].mean(),2))

The mean winning age is: 30.42
A Seaborn histogram is used to plot the age distribution, with the age on the x-axis, and the count on the y-axis. The data is approximately normally distributed around the age of 30, which is inline with our mean calculation (30.42) from the previous cell, and most of the wins occur between the age of 25 and 35.
Many drivers begin their career in their late teens, or early twenties, so we can conclude from this data that it takes a long time, on average, for a driver to start winning races. Aside from driver experience, this is likely due to the fact that most drivers start at a lower tier team, before working their way up the ladder, as only a handful of teams are able to compete for wins given the wide disparity in team finances.

Comparing Final Race Status Over Two 25 Year Periods¶

For the next plot, I created two new dataframes representing the first 25 years, and second 25 years of data. By resetting the index, replacing the date with a standard numerical index, I was able to split the original dataframe in half with some simple arithmetic. This was done by calculating the amount of rows using the length function, then dividing it by two to find the mid point. These parameters were passed to the iloc function, which selects the row/column slice by index numbers.
In [60]:
# reset the index and temporarily store the data in a new df
temp_f1 = F1.reset_index()

# create two new data frames splitting the data in half 
first_25 = temp_f1.iloc[0:round(len(temp_f1)/2),:]
last_25 = temp_f1.iloc[round(len(temp_f1)/2):(len(temp_f1)+1),:]
Side-by-side pie plots from the Matplotlib libary were used to compare the two time periods. I created custom labels which included the percentage proportion of each category using the value_count() function, as this made it much easier to see the small percentages, which were overlapping on the initial plot.
We can see a big difference in the percentages from one period to the next. From 1972 to 1997, 42.6% of drivers retired from the race due to accidents or mechanical complications, and 13.8% of drivers withdrew before the race started. From 1997 to 2022, we can see that the number of drivers retiring from races fell to 25.6%, and the number who withdrew fell to 1.1%. We can conclude that formula one cars are significantly more reliable than their older counterparts. This is not surprising given the level of technological innovation that has occurred in recent decades, and a primary focus on safety in the development process to protect the drivers as much as possible.
In [61]:
# create the legend labels for each pie plot
status = F1['final_status'].unique().tolist()

Another way to visualise points earned throughout the season, and the dominance of the two best drivers, is by plotting the cumulative points earned by each driver as the season progressed. Using a similar pivot approach, I was able to sum the points earned by each driver using the cumsum() function. The resulting dataframe was then used to create a Seaborn line plot. The dominance of the two drivers is clear to see, and gap between them and the rest of the field only widened as the season progressed.

# reset the index and create a new pivot table from the dataframe
s21_points = season_21.reset_index()
s21_points = s21_points.pivot('race_date', 'driver_name', 'points')
s21_points = s21_points.cumsum()

Visualising the Position Differential of Each Driver¶

For the next plot, a new column called 'position_diff' was created by subtracting the finish position from the start position for each driver, for each race over the season. This provides us with look at how well drivers were able to make up ground throughout the race, or if they generally lost positions after qualifying.

In [66]:
# create a new column called position difference: start position - finish position
season_21['position_diff'] = season_21['start_pos'] - season_21['final_pos']

# show the first 5 rows

A helpful way to visualise this relationship is with a bar plot, which shows the positional value, as well as the standard error (represented by the black lines over the bar). There are some caveats to this analysis: drivers who qualify near the front of the grid can only make up a limited amount of positions, and drivers who qualify near the back of the grid have more of an opportunity to climb, so the appropriate way to use this data is to compare drivers who generally qualify around a similar place to each other.

Lewis Hamilton, Lando Norris, and Estaban Ocon showed an impressive level of consistancy with minimal variance. While Sergio Perez and Pierre Gasly, who are both considered to be some of the most talented drivers on the grid, had statistically poor seasons, with a negative differential and a large variance in their performances.

Lap Times Over the 2021 Season¶

The final plot uses the subplot functionality of Matplotlib, which allows us to plot multiple box plots on an underlying grid. To prepare the data for this plot, I created a list containing the names of each race, using the unique() function to remove duplicates. The Belgian Grand Prix was removed from the list as lap time data was missing for this race.

To cleanly plot the data, I used a loop and the zip function, which creates a tuple of the two objects passed as parameters, allowing us to iterate over them; and the ravel() function, which converts the axs from a two-dimensional array to a one-dimensional array, allowing us to iterate over it sequentially. I then plotted the unique race name's on the y-axis, using the boolean conditional filter, and the lap times of each driver on the x-axis.

We can see a mostly tight spread in the data for each race, evidenced by the relatively small range in x-tick values. There will always be outliers, as some cars suffer mechanical or performance issues, but for the most part, there isn't a lot to split the cars on a lap-by-lap basis.

In [71]:
# create a list of races by using the unique function on the race_name Series, and then convert it to a list
races = season_21['race_name'].unique().tolist()
races.remove('Belgian Grand Prix')

# create the subplot and axes, and set the figure title
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=7, ncols=3, figsize=(15, 12))
fig.suptitle("Lap Times for Drivers Over the 2021 Season", fontsize=20)

# loop through the race list and axs, using the ravel function, which converts it from a 2d to 1d array
for race, ax in zip(races, axs.ravel()):
    # filter df for ticker and plot on specified axes
    sns.boxplot(y=season_21[(season_21['race_name'] == race)]['race_name'], x='fastest_lap_time', data=season_21, ax=ax)
    ax.set_xlabel('Lap time (seconds)', labelpad=15)
    ax.set_ylabel('')

# remove unnecessary space
fig.tight_layout()
